  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve red or white wine with turkey at Thanksgiving?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Both work beautifully, but it depends on your preparation and guest preferences. Light to medium-bodied reds like Pinot Noir complement roasted turkey's savory flavors without overwhelming the meat, while crisp whites like Chardonnay or Riesling pair excellently with herb-rubbed turkey and creamy sides. For maximum flexibility, offer one of each style to accommodate different palates and the variety of dishes on your table.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine pairs best with cranberry sauce and sweet Thanksgiving sides?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Off-dry wines with bright acidity are your best bet for sweet and tart Thanksgiving sides. German Riesling, Gewürztraminer, or Chenin Blanc have enough residual sugar to complement cranberry sauce while their acidity cuts through rich sweet potato casserole. The slight sweetness in these wines creates harmony rather than competition with your holiday's sweeter elements.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How much wine should I buy for a Thanksgiving dinner party?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Plan for about half a bottle per person for a typical 3-4 hour Thanksgiving celebration. For a party of 8, purchase 4-5 bottles, mixing 2-3 reds and 2 whites to accommodate different preferences. Consider having one extra bottle on hand, as holiday gatherings often run longer than expected and guests may want to continue celebrating.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing Thanksgiving wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is selecting wines that are too bold or tannic, which clash with the meal's diverse flavors and textures. Heavy Cabernet Sauvignon or oaked Chardonnay can overpower turkey and vegetables, while also competing with rich gravies and stuffing. Instead, choose food-friendly wines with moderate alcohol and balanced acidity that complement rather than dominate the feast.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good budget-friendly wines that work for Thanksgiving?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely! Look for American Pinot Noir from Oregon ($15-25), Spanish Garnacha ($12-18), or Portuguese Vinho Verde ($10-15) for excellent value. These regions produce food-friendly wines with the right balance of fruit, acidity, and moderate alcohol that pair beautifully with turkey dinner. Many quality producers offer their "second labels" or regional blends that deliver great taste without premium pricing.</p>
